# iwssim-gpu native-RGB perf probe metadata
# Commit: filled at commit time
# Host: water-cooled AMD Ryzen 9 7950X, 128 GB RAM, RTX 5070 (driver 596.21, CUDA 13.2)
# Date: 2026-05-26
# Backend: cubecl-cuda
# Command:
#   cargo run --release -p iwssim-gpu --example native_rgb_perf_probe \
#       --no-default-features --features cubecl-types,cuda
#
# Workload (per size): 1 cached reference + 20 distortion calls. Three modes:
#   - host_conv:        compute_with_reference_stripped(host_BT601(dis_rgb))
#                       — production path today. host_conv_ms measures the
#                         per-call host-side rgb→gray work; gpu_compute_ms
#                         is the strip walker + readback.
#   - gray_baseline:    compute_with_reference_stripped(prebuilt_dis_gray)
#                       — lower bound, host conversion done outside the
#                         timing loop. Tells us what the strip walker
#                         costs by itself.
#   - native_rgb_strip: compute_rgb_with_reference_stripped_native(dis_rgb)
#                       — this commit's implementation. Per strip:
#                         pack_into_pinned(dis_strip_rgb) + alloc empty
#                         g_dis_strip + rgb_u32_to_gray_kernel + strip walker.
#
# Strip body for these sizes: 256² maps to body=256 (1 strip), 1024²/2048²
# /4096² map to body=1024.
#
# Columns:
#   w_h:                 image dimensions "WxH"
#   mp:                  megapixels
#   mode:                "host_conv" / "gray_baseline" / "native_rgb_strip"
#   n_iter:              dist calls per mode (20)
#   host_conv_ms:        mean ms/call of host-side BT.601 rgb→gray. 0 for
#                        gray_baseline and native_rgb_strip.
#   gpu_compute_ms:      mean ms/call from dist input ready (gray for the
#                        first two, RGB for native) through compute_*
#                        + client.sync.
#   total_ms:            host_conv_ms + gpu_compute_ms.
#   host_conv_share_pct: host_conv_ms / total_ms * 100. Used by the
#                        decision rule (> 10% → SHIP, < 5% → DON'T SHIP).
#   score:               final IW-SSIM score of the last dist (sanity gate
#                        that the three paths produce identical outputs).
#
# Key findings (across 4 runs of the probe):
#
# 1. Host-conv share of wall time:
#      256²:   8-12% (sub-ms absolute, marginal)
#      1024²:  35-41%
#      2048²:  6-40% (high variance — see contention note below)
#      4096²:  13-26%
#    At 1024² and above, host-side rgb→gray is consistently a double-digit
#    fraction of wall time. The brief's threshold (> 10% at any size) is
#    cleanly cleared.
#
# 2. GPU contention: this machine was running 5+ sibling jj workspaces
#    in parallel (cvvdp/ssim2/dssim/zensim), all on the same RTX 5070.
#    `nvidia-smi` reported 105-141 MiB free out of ~12 GB during these
#    runs and 0-78% utilisation across timesteps. This is the dominant
#    noise source — host_conv numbers vary by 2-3× across runs at 4096²
#    (60-69ms host_conv at 4096² was stable; gpu_compute_ms ranged
#    95-431ms for the same code path). Treat absolute timings as a rough
#    sketch; the host_conv_share fraction is more reliable because both
#    numerator and denominator share the same contention.
#
# 3. The native_rgb_strip implementation in this commit (commits TBD):
#      256²:   ~tied with host_conv (sub-ms anyway)
#      1024²:  HIGHLY VARIABLE — winning by 56% in one run (10ms vs
#              23ms), losing by 220-436% in others (37-48ms vs 9-12ms).
#      2048²:  WINS in 3 of 4 runs (avg ~30ms vs ~70ms host_conv, but
#              one run flipped on contention).
#      4096²:  LOSES in all 4 runs (avg ~470ms vs ~330ms host_conv).
#
#    Root cause of the loss at 4096²: the naive implementation allocates
#    a fresh packed-u32 staging handle AND a fresh g_dis_strip handle
#    per strip, then runs an extra kernel launch per strip. At 4096²
#    with body=1024 + halo=256, there are 4-5 strips per call → 8-10
#    extra device allocations + 4-5 extra kernel launches per call,
#    vs the gray-baseline path's 4-5 `create_from_slice` calls. The
#    extra alloc + launch overhead outweighs the saved host conversion.
#
# DECISION:
#   - Host-conv share fraction CLEARLY justifies investigating a native
#     RGB strip path (35-41% at 1024², the production target size).
#   - The naive implementation in this commit is parity-correct (see
#     tests/rgb_strip_native.rs, all 7 tests pass) but NOT a consistent
#     wall-time win. It needs follow-up work:
#       a) Reuse g_dis_strip across strips (don't alloc per-strip).
#       b) Reuse a single whole-image packed-u32 pinned staging buffer
#          and have the kernel take a strip offset, instead of packing
#          per strip.
#       c) Consider a fused pack+convert kernel that reads sRGB-u8
#          directly (skip the host-side 3→4 byte pack entirely).
#   - The implementation is committed for completeness + future
#     reference; the perf optimisation is queued as a follow-up.
#
# Scores match across all three paths to f32 precision (column "score"
# above — 0.064713 / 0.060277 / 0.062326 / 0.063340 are identical
# across host_conv / gray_baseline / native_rgb_strip per size, modulo
# 1-ULP differences in the BT.601 rounding that occasionally flip the
# 6th decimal: 2048² native shows 0.062325 vs 0.062326 for the other
# two, which is within the 5e-5 relative bound the parity test enforces).
